$$f(x) = -6-21x-2x^{ 2 }$$

Write down the first derivative, \(f^\prime(x)\), and find the value of \(x\) that maximizes \(f(x)\).

solution:
$$f^\prime(x) = -21-4x$$

\(f(x)\) is maximized at \(x=-5.25\). The maximum value of \(f(x)\) is 49.125.

Write down the first derivative, \(f^\prime(x)\), and find the value of \(x\) that maximizes \(f(x)\). 
What is the maximum value of \(f(x)\)?
solution:
$$f^\prime(x) = 18x^{ -3 / 4 }-18 $$

\(f(x)\) is maximized at \(x=1\). The maximum value of \(f(x)\) is 54.
